# try, catch, throw 🤹

1.  **try:** Block of code that might cause an error.
2.  **throw:** Signals that an error has occurred.
3.  **catch:** Block that handles the error.

```cpp
try {
    // Risky code
    throw 10;
} catch (int e) {
    // Handled here
} 
```

# Division by Zero ➗

```cpp
int numerator = 10, denominator = 0;

try {
    if (denominator == 0) {
        throw "Division by Zero!";
    }
    cout << numerator / denominator;
} 
catch (const char* msg) {
    cerr << "Error: " << msg << endl;
}
```
Here, we throw a string message and catch it.

# Catching Them All 🥅

A try block can throw different types of exceptions.

```cpp
try {
    if (x == 0) throw 10;     // int
    if (x == 1) throw 'a';    // char
} 
catch (int x)  { ... } 
catch (char c) { ... }
```

**Catch All:** `catch (...)` handles any type of exception not caught by previous blocks. Use it as a last resort.

# Built-in Errors 📚

C++ provides a standard hierarchy of exceptions in `<stdexcept>`.

- `std::exception` (Base class)
- `std::logic_error`
- `std::runtime_error`

```cpp
#include <stdexcept>

throw runtime_error("Something bad happened");

catch (const std::exception& e) {
    cout << e.what(); // Prints the message
}
```

